# aks-node-debug Python code 

A Python-based `kubectl` plugin that simplifies node-level troubleshooting in Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS).

The plugin lists the available AKS nodes, lets you select one interactively, and starts a debug session using `kubectl debug`.

## Features

* Lists available AKS nodes
* Provides interactive node selection
* Starts a `kubectl debug` session on the selected node
* Uses an AKS-compatible debug image
* Runs as a standard `kubectl` plugin

## Prerequisites

* Python 3
* `kubectl`
* Azure CLI
* Access to an AKS cluster
* Current Kubernetes context configured for AKS
* Permissions to list nodes and create debug pods

## Local Installation

Clone the repository:

```bash
git clone https://github.com/ragatgen/kubectl-aks-node-debug.git
cd kubectl-aks-node-debug
```

Make the plugin executable:

```bash
chmod +x kubectl-aks-node-debug
```

Create a local plugin directory:

```bash
mkdir -p ~/bin
mv kubectl-aks-node-debug ~/bin/
export PATH="$HOME/bin:$PATH"
```

Verify that `kubectl` detects the plugin:

```bash
kubectl plugin list
```

Expected output:

```text
/home/<user>/bin/kubectl-aks-node-debug
```

## Usage

Depending on your local `kubectl` plugin resolution, run:

```bash
kubectl aks node debug
```

You can also run the plugin directly:

```bash
~/bin/kubectl-aks-node-debug
```

## Example

```text
Available nodes in your AKS cluster:

1) aks-default-99999999-vmss000000
2) aks-default-99999999-vmss000001
3) aks-default-99999999-vmss000002

Choose one node by number: 2

You selected: aks-default-99999999-vmss000001
Starting debug session on node: aks-default-99999999-vmss000001

root@aks-default-99999999:/#
```

## Help

```bash
kubectl aks node debug --help
```

or:

```bash
